		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Decibel</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Decibel_(disambiguation)" title="Decibel (disambiguation)">Decibel (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p>The <b>decibel</b> (<b>dB</b>) is a <a href="/wiki/Logarithmic_units" title="Logarithmic units" class="mw-redirect">logarithmic unit</a> of measurement that expresses the magnitude of a physical quantity (usually <a href="/wiki/Power_(physics)" title="Power (physics)">power</a> or <a href="/wiki/Intensity_(physics)" title="Intensity (physics)">intensity</a>) relative to a specified or implied <i>reference level</i>. Since it expresses a ratio of two quantities with the same unit, it is a <a href="/wiki/Dimensionless_unit" title="Dimensionless unit" class="mw-redirect">dimensionless unit</a>. A decibel is one tenth of a <b>bel</b> (<b>B</b>).</p>
<p>The decibel is useful for a wide variety of measurements in science and <a href="/wiki/Engineering" title="Engineering">engineering</a> (e.g., <a href="/wiki/Acoustics" title="Acoustics">acoustics</a> and <a href="/wiki/Electronics" title="Electronics">electronics</a>) and other disciplines. It confers a number of advantages, such as the ability to conveniently represent very large or small numbers, a logarithmic scaling that roughly corresponds to the human perception of, for example, sound and light, and the ability to carry out multiplication of ratios by simple addition and subtraction.</p>
<p>The decibel symbol is often qualified with a suffix, which indicates which reference quantity or <a href="/wiki/A-weighting" title="A-weighting">frequency weighting function</a> has been used. For example, "dBm" indicates that the reference quantity is one <a href="/wiki/Milliwatt" title="Milliwatt" class="mw-redirect">milliwatt</a>, while "dBu" is referenced to 0.775 <a href="/wiki/Volts" title="Volts" class="mw-redirect">volts</a> <a href="/wiki/Root_mean_square" title="Root mean square">RMS</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-clqgmk_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-clqgmk-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The definitions of the decibel and bel use base-10 logarithms. For a similar unit using natural logarithms to base <i>e</i>, see <a href="/wiki/Neper" title="Neper">neper</a>.</p>
